Data Science – Midterm report¶

Building a Regression Model¶

1. Introduction to the domain-specific area¶

The domain-specific area for this project will focus on the biological data of pacific salmon.
Specifically, we will be trying to use a logical regression model to predict salmon weight according to a few key attributes – species, length, salt water age, fresh water age, etc.

Salmon and its species, as with many animals, come in different shapes and sizes. Of the 5 pacific salmon species in the dataset, we can quickly understand the size (length / weight) attributes as per internet sources:

  • Chinook: Adult fish range in size from 61 to 91 cm, but may be up to 150 cm in length; they average 4.5 to 22.7 kg, but may reach 59 kg[1]
  • Chum: Adult chum salmon usually weigh from 4.4 to 10.0 kg with an average length of 60.0 cm[2]
  • Coho: Mature adults average 71 cm and 3.2 to 5.0 kg, occasionally reaching up to 16 kg[3]
  • Pink: Pink salmon average 2.2 kg in weight. The maximum recorded size was 76 cm and 6.8 kg[4]
  • Sockeye: Sockeye can be anywhere from 60 to 84 cm in length and weigh from 2.3 to 7 kg[5]

As we can see from the general description, the 5 species of pacific salmon differ in length and weight. And that will also produce a unique length to weight ratio. Although the of the salmon is quite similar at around 60+ cm for all 5 species, the weight differs quite a bit between each species. Although this report will not focus specifically on the internal biological differences, we can generally understand the variance to be attributed to the difference in bone density, skin thickness, fat content, internal organ size, width of salmon, etc.

The below picture can provide a visual reference to the size difference between these 5 species[6].

Even before looking at the data, we can quickly understand that there are obvious physical differences between the 5 species of salmon. Specifically, the Chinook salmon is much larger than the others. The pink salmon appears the be the smallest.

A possible application for the prediction of weight of a salmon within a wild and natural habitat is to provide more datapoints for species identification. An example of a similar solution has been deployed in Norway where an AI powered filtering system is used to filter out invasive species of salmon[8]. The system needs to identify and categorize the salmon into either the local Atlantic salmon or invasive Pacific salmon to allow or deny access to the upstream channel.

In this case of this, the camera can be set up to capture the length of the sample, but gathering the weight would be difficult in a real-life environment due to many variables. When the weight is predicted, the length of the sample with the predicted weight could be used in another machine learning classification model (perhaps logistical regression) to predict the species of salmon.

Description of the selected dataset¶

The dataset acquired from Kaggle describes it as “60 years of measurements from 12.5 million salmon across Alaska”. It also attributes the data to another source [9].

The dataset can be described as biological data of salmon samples collected in Alaska from 1922-2017. In total, the dataset includes just over 14.3 million samples (14,347,460 actual entries) of salmon covering 5 pacific species -- chinook, chum, coho, pink and sockeye.

The dataset also includes 27 columns of data including age, sex and length, weight, sample date, measurement method, saltwater/ freshwater age, and other classification data. As can be expected for such a large dataset spanning over 60 years of sampling carried out by multiple teams with differing technology available at the time, the completeness of the data varies across all aspect. Luckily, with so many samples, discarding incomplete samples to gather usable data can still yield a favorable sample size for the project.

The columns of interest for this project:

  • Species
  • Sample year
  • Sample date
  • Length
  • Weight
  • Sex
  • Data source

The first task was to analyze the raw dataset in using pandas. We can load it from the CSV file into a data frame and print the head using df_salmon1.head()

From the screenshot, we can see that the dataset includes 27 columns of information, but not all will be usable in the context of this project. What we really interested in is the values length, weight, sex, and age. We can further filter out the dataset to see roughly how many rows are usable by checking the invalid data in the weight column with df_salmon1.isna().sum()

So, we can see that in the Weight column, it returned just over 13.6 million rows that are not usable for this project. 14,347,460 – 13,670,088 = 677,372 usable entries

Perhaps, after further data cleaning, we will end up with less than ~677k entries, but it has been decided that this specific dataset is for this project is suitable and should yield a good cleaned up amount of data.

Objectives of the project¶

The objective of this project is to use the length data of the specific salmon species to predict the weight. Length and weight datapoints will be gathered from the dataset and filtered down to a desired manageable dataset with all the required datapoints present.

The processed data will be used for the Scikit-learn regression model based on the Support Vector Regression, which is great for working with continuous values. Length data will be inputted and weight will be predicted by the model.

When implemented, it can augment existing classification machine learning models by adding an extra layer of data verification. Ideally, this would be used early on when gathering data, like mentioned in the example of the similar solution has been deployed as an AI powered salmon filtering system in Norway, it can help in gathering real time data of the length of the sample salmon and predict the weight for further classification models downstream.

The advantage is that it can predict and provide real time data for models and allow the classification models to better classify according to live data.

Machine learning section¶

For the machine learning part, I have decided to use the Support Vector Regression (SVR) method to create a regression model. The reason for selecting this method is for a few reasons:

  • SVR is a version of the already popular SVM for regression
  • Supported by scikit-learn library with choice of multiple implementation methods
  • SVR performs better performance prediction than other algorithms like Linear Regression, KNN and Elastic Net [10]

As stated in the beginning, the goal is to predict the weight of a new sample of salmon according to the species of salmon with the length.

  • Label (y value) would be the weight of the salmon sample
  • Feature (X value) would be the length of the salmon

The reason for selecting the labels and features is due to our hypothetical situation of the AI salmon species identification, we can only gather the length of the salmon in real time.

Now, we will print out 3 popular metrics for evaluating our SVR model:

  • R2 score — the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable(s)[11]. Closer to 1 = better
  • Mean Absolute Error — a measure of errors between paired observations expressing the same phenomenon[12]. Lower = better
  • Root Mean Squared Error —a measure of the differences between values (sample) predicted by a model or an estimator and the values observed[13]. Lower = better

Conclusions¶

The results of the both SVR models matched the actual values quite closely. It is believed that if deployed in the above-mentioned scenario of the AI salmon species identification, weight could be predicted to an accurate degree which closely follows the actually regression line.

The metrics for both ML model #1 and ML model #2 are quite similar in terms of R^2, MAE, and RMSE, but the visual data showed a slight difference. The ML model #2 performed slightly better at the higher end of the features (x value) input.

The project overall was a success in achieving the original goal mentioned in the first part of the report. Most of the effort was spent on the processing of the data. It is believed that unprocessed data would not be able to achieve this result, but at the same time, the highly processed data already fit the regression line before the application of machine learning model. Perhaps the data may have been too processed, which resulted in a favorable result. Maybe with enough time, it is worth exploring an alternate control scenario by providing the ML models with less processed data and interpreting the results.
